Filling out the Convention Card:  The Front of the Card: Opening 2-level:
A word about agreements. Unless you play something pretty odd, 2@c is strong, forcing, and artificial. It should show 
a hand with enough playing strength to be able to play at the 3-level opposite a bust, or at most 4 losers; 
I also think that the 2@C bid usually shows at least 6 "controls" (where A = 2 and K = 1 control). 
Examples of strong 2@c hands:  Which of these hands open 2@C?

1: @sAKJ109x   @hx   @DKQJx   @CAKx

Answer: Clearly enough stuff--21 HCP and 4 losers. 

2: @sQx   @hKQJ10xxx   @DAKJx   @CQ

Answer: Will make 4@h opposite as little as an Ace.  But the lack of controls makes me cautious (with an Ace and 
2 Kings, responder would think about slam). Open this hand 1@H. 

3: @sKQJx   @hAx   @DKQJx   @CAQx

Answer: Open 2@C and rebid 2NT.  That sequence shows 22-24 HCP balanced hand (may have 5-card Major -- use 
puppet stayman in this sequence) 2@C - 2@d / 2NT.  
Our NT ladder is: 20=21 opens 2NT, 22-24 opens 2@C, rebids 2NT, 25-27 opens 2@C, rebids 3NT.
If you are worrying about hearts... don’t!  Your job is to bid what your hand is, and this looks like 22-24 HCP 
balanced, hence 2@C -> 2NT.  You want to open or rebid NT (after 2@C) whenever your hand is balanced and in range.

You want to learn Puppet Stayman to find 5-3 fits when responder has a 3-card Major and a doubleton outside. 
If the "short" hand is taking a ruff, you want to be in a trump suit with 5-3 fit. Otherwise, if NT is playable, you 
generally take the same number of tricks in 5-3 fit at NT or the Major. |
pg| ***** 5 ***** |


nt||ht|c|cp|2|at|^b@2
4: @sAx   @hAQJ10xxx   @Dxxx   @CA

Answer:  NOT a 2@C opener, as it has 5 losers (open 1@h and plan to rebid 4@h over most responses).


5: @sAKxx   @hAKQx   @Dx   @CAQxx

Answer: Even with 22 HCP, open 1@C. 4441 hands are very hard to bid, and unless you find a fit, the hand will be 
hard to play.  Plan to raise 1 of a Major to 4 (or splinter to 4@d). 

6: @sAKQ10xx   @hAKQx   @Dx   @Cxx

Answer:  With 6 controls and very strong suits, open 2@C.  So what if you have "only" 18 HCP? You will make game 
when pard has as little as the 2 Major suit Jacks, or 2 hearts and @sJxx.  In this case, you need  hearts to divide 
4-3 or if they are 5-2 with a 2-2 spade split,  or if both suits split poorly, for the long heart to be with the long 
spade, about an 80% chance.  One of my regular partners thinks this hand opens 1@S. He and I discussed it at length. 
The argument for 1@S is to get your suit in before the opponents start pushing the auction with minor suit bids.  
My argument is that partner won't ever compete unless you start with 2@c.

Marty Bergen's latest booklet gives this advice - when you have a powerhouse hand, open 2@c; 
it'll make subsequent bidding easier.
So there it is, our brief overview of 2@C opener.  Now let's look at responding.
First, let's examine what a positive response should be.
You should bid 2@D most of the time.  When you bid 2@H or 2@S you show a decent 5-card suit, KQ10xx or better 
(the suit has 1 loser at most = 2 of the top 3 honors) AND an outside control (A or K).
This is the WEAKEST hand I would ever treat as a positive: @sKQ109x, @hxx, @DKJx, @Cxxx. This hand is good enough 
that opener should think about a slam with any kind of spade fit (Axx or any 4 spades).|
pg| ***** 6 ***** |


nt||ht|c|cp|2|at|^b@2
Basically, a positive response to 2@c suggests the strength to look for slam if a fit and controls work.  A positive
shows a good suit and an entry to it. 
Responder should not be in a hurry to bid NT after 2@C opening.  I think it shows 4333, no major, and around 9-10 HCP.
For the 2@C box on 2 bids, we check off "Strong", and 2@D is now a waiting bid.
We use cheaper minor as "second negative." (Some older texts say 2NT should be used as second negative.
Experience teaches that you get into trouble with 2NT by the weak hand.)

NOTE: Some people use 2@h as a super negative over 2@C, showing zero aces/kings, and fewer than 5 HCP. This 
works, but you have to consider that a 2@h supernegative wrongsides hearts when that is the big hand's suit.

We note that 2@C shows at most 4 losers, is forcing for 1 round (only way to stop at 2 level is 2@C - 2@D/ 2N - p).

kat827: How does KQ10xx (above) just have 1 loser?  Wouldn't the A and J win tricks against this holding?
mitche:  We could lose 2 tricks, but we treat a suit w/2 of top 3 honors and length as 1 loser.

Next: weak 2 bids:  2@D, 2@h, 2@S are weak 2's. These bids show between 6-10 HCP and promise a 6-card suit.
If you learn only 1 thing in this lesson, here is the point: YOU MUST AGREE WITH YOUR PARTNER ON YOUR
STYLE FOR OPENING WEAK 2'S. Some expert players (Sabine Auken, one of the world's strongest players, for example)
will open weak 2's on helium.  I saw her open 2@S in first seat on @sJ10xxxx, @hx, @DQxx, @CQJx (no one vulnerable).

Unless you are a world-class declarer, I recommend these 2 ideas:  
First, more of your points should be IN your long suit than outside it. A weak 2 is primarily an OFFENSIVE hand.
Second, avoid preempting with good support for an unbid Major.
You can guess from these remarks that I prefer disciplined weak 2's in first and (especially) second seats.|
pg| ***** 7 ***** |


nt||ht|c|cp|2|at|^b@2We agree on these treatments of weak 2's:

1: RONF ("Raise Only Non Forcing)
Any raise of a weak 2 is non-forcing. Any new suit by unpassed responder is 100% forcing for 1 round; 
The weak 2 bidder is expected to raise partner's new suit with a 3-card support if it was a Major.  

2: 2NT is FEATURE ASKING. Opener rebids 3 of her suit with a weak suit. With KQ10xxx or better and an outside 
A or K, opener bids the suit with the feature. 
Some pairs use the Ogust convention, which I like, too. But since first/second seat weak 2's are disciplined, you don't gain very much with it, and FA is easier to remember and use correctly.  (If you happen to be Sabine Auken, use Ogust.)

A final word on weak 2's.  My good friend, the late Maryann Dufresne, in her book, "Bridge with bells and whistles"
(a very good book, I might add) said "don't tell the same story twice."  If you stick to disciplined weak 2's, you
have told your entire story with your weak 2 bid. Don't bid again unless responder asks you to.  
So for 2@d, 2@h and 2@s we show for point count, 5-10 (and note, it's pretty rare to open a weak 2 with just 5 HCP).  
We check off 2NT as forcing, and write "Feature Asking."

One note: someone mentioned that they prefer to play new suit as non-forcing. 
I can't be nagging you at the table, so I will do it here: 
It makes life too hard to use 2NT as the only forcing bid.
Here is why:
Suppose your hand is @sAKJxx   @hx   @DKQJx   @CAxx    and pard opens 2@h. 
If 2@s is non-forcing.... you need to bid 2NT and follow up with 3@S, which puts responder under terrible pressure with 
something like @sxxx   @hKQJxxx   @dxx   @cQx   
Game is maybe making.  But it's possible that 3@S is the limit of the hand, and the 2@h opener will never know if it's right to raise or pass.  
You see the problems that making 2@S non forcing introduces?
While:     2@h - 2@s / 3@s (showing a 3-card support) let's responder decide whether to continue or not
(Of course responder bids the new suit to find a better fit, and may or may not want to move on)
OK, let's play some bridge! 



