OK, it's already past bidding bedtime. Here is a brief supplement on Bergen raises.
The LOTT (Law of total tricks) says that you're "safe" to bid to a level equal to the number of trumps your side has.
Bergen raises are designed to follow the LOTT.  
When opener begins with 1@h or 1@S, promising 5, responder will bid to 3-level with 4-card support.

Here is the idea (in this discussion responder always has 4-card support for opener's Major): 

With 0-6 HCP (and hopefully side shortness), responder bids 3 of the Major, 
a WEAK bid designed to take up as much bidding room as possible and get to the LAWful level as fast as possible.  
So 1@S - 3@S shows a hand like K10xx, xx, xxxxx, xx      or thereabouts.  

If responder  has 4-card support and 7-9 points, he jumps to 3@C 
so 1@S - 3@C shows a hand like this:  
@sQJxx   @hxx   @DKQxx   @CJ10x    or maybe    @sAxxx   @hxx   @DKxx   @Cxxxx.     But not much more than that.

And finally, 1@S - 3@D shows a 4-card limit raise, about 10-11 dummy points, something like: 
@s10xxx   @hAQx   @Dxx   @CKQxx
Note that if your partnership allows very light opening bids, then you may need to adjust your HCP totals for 
3@C and 3@D up by a point.

And finally, with 4+ trumps and 13+ dummy points, use Jacoby 2NT or Splinter
Splintering:  
If responder has a 4+ card support, a singleton or void, and 13-15 dummy points (counting distribution), a splinter 
is a much better idea than J2NT.
Example:  @sx   @hK10xx   @DAxx   @CKQ10xx    is good enough to bid 3@S over 1@h.
(MM: More than "good enough", I am counting 12 HCP, +1 length, +1 Quality @c, + 3 for the singleton.. = 17-isch, too strong for the splinter)
